To write an enum class representing different request types, you can define an enum with constants representing each request type. Here's an example:

```java
public enum RequestType {
    GET,
    POST,
    PUT,
    DELETE
}
```

In this example, the `RequestType` enum class has four constants: `GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, and `DELETE`, representing different HTTP request types.

You can then use this enum in your code to store or compare request types. For example:

```java
@GetMapping("/v1")
public String testMethod(HttpServletRequest request) {
    RequestType requestType = RequestType.valueOf(request.getMethod());

    switch (requestType) {
        case GET:
            // Handle GET request
            break;
        case POST:
            // Handle POST request
            break;
        case PUT:
            // Handle PUT request
            break;
        case DELETE:
            // Handle DELETE request
            break;
        default:
            // Handle unknown request type
            break;
    }

    // Rest of the code
}
```

In this example, `request.getMethod()` retrieves the HTTP method of the request. Then, using `RequestType.valueOf(request.getMethod())`, you can convert the string representation of the method to the corresponding enum constant.

By using the enum constants, you can easily perform comparisons or switch case statements based on the request type.
